  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are statutes that address money laundering in many jurisdictions around the world. In the United States, the primary federal statute addressing money laundering is the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, which is codified at **18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957**. These statutes criminalize various activities related to money laundering, including:\n\n1. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: This section makes it a crime to knowingly conduct or attempt to conduct a financial transaction involving the proceeds of specified unlawful activity (SUA) with the intent to promote further illegal activity, conceal the nature of the proceeds, avoid reporting requirements, or evade taxes.\n\n2. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: This section prohibits individuals from knowingly engaging in monetary transactions exceeding $10,000 in criminally derived property. This applies to transactions that involve funds derived from specified unlawful activities.\n\nAdditionally, the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**, enacted in 1970, requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering by maintaining records, filing reports, and implementing anti-money laundering (AML) programs.\n\nIn other countries, similar laws exist to combat money laundering. For example:\n\n- In the **European Union**, money laundering is addressed by the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**, which harmonize regulations across member states.\n- In the **United Kingdom**, the **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002** (POCA) is the primary legislation targeting money laundering.\n- In **Canada**, the **Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act** governs AML efforts.\n\nInternational organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** also play a key role in setting global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Many countries have adopted FATF recommendations into their domestic laws.\n\nThese statutes and frameworks aim to prevent the integration of illicit funds into the legitimate financial system and hold individuals and organizations accountable for facilitating or participating in money laundering activities.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
